## 1. Introduction

<!-- TODO: Develop into flowing prose -->

When I redesigned this website, I wanted to rethink the photo gallery. The previous version used CSS columns (via Tailwind) â€” a layout that fills top-to-bottom, left-to-right, and lets portrait photos dominate the page. It prioritized space efficiency over equal representation.

I wanted something different: a gallery where landscape and portrait photos receive equal visual weight, without cropping, without JavaScript layout calculations, and with a tactile, physical feel â€” like prints pinned to a wall.

This post documents the layout I designed and the trade-offs involved.

### Navigational vs. Editorial Galleries

Before diving in, a distinction: there are two fundamentally different types of photo galleries.

**Editorial galleries** are story-driven. The photographer controls visual hierarchy â€” some photos appear larger, creating emphasis and narrative flow. The sequence tells a story.

**Navigational galleries** serve a different purpose: presenting all photos equally, letting the viewer control the order (by date, popularity, tags). The goal is discovery, not storytelling.

This post focuses on **navigational galleries** â€” where equal presentation matters.

