### 3.2 Column Layouts (Pinterest, Unsplash)

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

Fixed column widths, variable heights. Photos keep their original aspect ratio.

```css
.gallery {
  columns: 3;
  column-gap: 1rem;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
```

![Column-based layout](./assets/columns.svg "Column layout â€” portrait photos dominate visually")

**Trade-off:** Preserves aspect ratio, maximizes space usage, but:

- **Portrait photos dominate** â€” taller images occupy more area, drawing more attention
- Captions under variable-height images create uneven spacing

#### Rhythm: Vertical Stripes Only

Column edges create strong vertical leading lines â€” horizontal rhythm as you scan left-to-right. But photos have different heights, so horizontal transitions occur at different positions. No alignment, no vertical leading lines.

![Column layout with leading lines](./assets/columns-leading-lines.svg "Only vertical leading lines form â€” horizontal transitions are scattered")

The result: monotonous vertical stripes.

#### The Fill Order Problem

CSS multi-column fills top-to-bottom, then moves to the next column â€” inherited from text layout.

![CSS column fill order](./assets/columns-CSS-order.svg "Pure CSS: 1-2 in first column, 3-4 in second, 5-6 in third")

With longer galleries, this becomes problematic. Recent photos (which users want to see first) end up at the bottom of the first column â€” below the fold:

![CSS column order with long gallery](./assets/columns-CSS-order-long.svg "With 10 photos, the first row shows 1, 5, 9 â€” photos 2, 3, 4 are hidden below")

Real implementations use JavaScript to place images left-to-right:

![Natural fill order](./assets/columns-natural-order.svg "JavaScript-controlled order: row by row, left to right")

![Unsplash â€” column layout](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/unsplash-columns.avif "Unsplash's column layout â€” portrait shots visually dominate")

