### 3.3 Justified Row Layouts (Flickr)

<!-- TODO: Develop prose -->

Photos arranged in rows, scaled so each row spans the full width. A JavaScript library determines how many photos fit per row to keep row heights roughly equal.

Flickr's open-source [justified-layout](https://github.com/flickr/justified-layout) library takes aspect ratios as input and outputs coordinates and dimensions.

![Justified row layout](./assets/justified.svg "Photos in each row share the same height, but row heights vary")

**Trade-off:** Preserves aspect ratio, but:

- **Requires JavaScript** â€” cannot be done with pure CSS
- **Landscape photos dominate** â€” wider images occupy more area within each row

#### Rhythm: Horizontal Lines Only

Row edges create strong horizontal leading lines â€” vertical rhythm as you scan top-to-bottom. But photos within rows have different widths, so vertical transitions don't align across rows.

![Justified layout with leading lines](./assets/justified-leading-lines.svg "Horizontal leading lines are strong â€” vertical transitions don't align")

More photos per row means smaller width variations, improving horizontal rhythm.

![Flickr justified layout](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/flickr-justified.avif "Flickr's justified layout â€” the landscape in row 1 dominates two portraits in row 2")

